    "\n",
    "From this dataset we are taking the metrics: Date, newCasesByPublishDate and newDeaths28DaysByPublishDate. This information is valuable to create models by using big data science techniques. In this analysis we are especially interested in forcasting 'Deaths' and 'Cases' in the future.\n",
    "\n",
    "Date is an index that spans since the beggining of the pandemic in the UK and is continually updated to this day.\n",
    "\n",
    "Deaths is a parameter that tells us the number of new deaths directly due to the pandemic.\n",
    "\n",
    "Cases is a parameter that tells us the number of new registered cases of COVID 19."
   ]

   "source": [
    "# failure function and API call\n",
    "def get_data(url):\n",
    "    response = get(URLandMetrics, timeout=10)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    if response.status_code >= 400:\n",
    "        raise RuntimeError(f'Request failed: { response.text }')\n",
    "        \n",
    "    return response.json()\n",
    "    \n",
    "#Our filters to get relevent information, this reduces cleaning later\n",
    "if __name__ == '__main__':\n",
    "    URLandMetrics = (\n",
    "        'https://api.coronavirus.data.gov.uk/v1/data?'\n",
    "        'filters=areaType=nation;areaName=england&'\n",
    "        'structure={\"date\":\"date\",\"newCases\":\"newCasesByPublishDate\",\"newDeaths\":\"newDeaths28DaysByPublishDate\"}'\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    \n",
    "    #calling the function with our chosen metrics\n",
    "    data = get_data(URLandMetrics)"
   ]
  },

This has a positive impact that the government can make decisions to 'flatten the curve' by enforcing lockdowns or vaccinations, or if there are a low number of cases predicted the government can use that information by reducing the restrictions."

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Solution 1: SIR Model\n",
    "## Introduction to Sir Model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The SIR Model is a specific model for predicting the spread of diseases, for this reason I found it was important to test this methods prediction against the actual outcome of this pandemic.\n",
    "\n",
    "This method has three dependent variables each as a function of time, those are; Susceptible individuals, Infected indiviuals and Recovered individuals.\n",
    "\n",
    "The advantage of this is that it allows us to input variables that other forcasting data models wouldn't know such as; Lockdown times, Contact rate of the infectious, recovery rate and how infectious the disease is and therefore should have advanteges in knowing when the pandemic will end and the last person will be cured of the Pandemic."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Application of the SIR Model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def sigmoid(x, xmin, xmax, a, b, c, r):\n",
    "    x_scaled = (x - xmin) / (xmax - xmin)\n",
    "    out = (a * np.exp(c * r) + b * np.exp(r * x_scaled)) / (np.exp(c * r) + np.exp(x_scaled * r))\n",
    "    return out\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def stepwise_soft(t, coefficients, r=20, c=0.5):\n",
    "    t_arr = np.array(list(coefficients.keys()))\n",
    "\n",
    "    min_index = np.min(t_arr)\n",
    "    max_index = np.max(t_arr)\n",
    "\n",
    "    if t <= min_index:\n",
    "        return coefficients[min_index]\n",
    "    elif t >= max_index:\n",
    "        return coefficients[max_index]\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        index = np.min(t_arr[t_arr >= t])\n",
    "\n",
    "    if len(t_arr[t_arr < index]) == 0:\n",
    "        return coefficients[index]\n",
    "    prev_index = np.max(t_arr[t_arr < index])\n",
    "    # sigmoid smoothing\n",
    "    q0, q1 = coefficients[prev_index], coefficients[index]\n",
    "    out = sigmoid(t, prev_index, index, q0, q1, c, r)\n",
    "    return out\n",
    "    \n",
    "    #starting date is 3rd February 2020\n",
    "    #49 days\n",
    "    #1st lockdown is 23rd March - 23rd June taking 92 days\n",
    "    #122 days\n",
    "    #2nd Lockdown is 23rd October - 2nd December taking 40 days\n",
    "t_range = np.arange(data[\"length\"])\n",
    "coefficients = {\n",
    "    0: 0,\n",
    "    50: 0.5,\n",
    "    49+92: 0,\n",
    "    49+92+122: 1,\n",
    "    49+92+122+40: 0.6\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title('Quarantine function example')\n",
    "plt.scatter(coefficients.keys(), coefficients.values(), label='Points of change of quarantine measures')\n",
    "plt.plot(t_range, [stepwise_soft(t, coefficients, r=20, c=0.5) for t in t_range], label='Smooth stepwise function')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Days')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Qaurantine and reduction in Contact level')\n",
    "plt.legend(loc='lower center', bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, -0.6),)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "By using the Covid timeline given to us by the UK government at:https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/charts/uk-government-coronavirus-lockdowns, we are able to find create coefficients that relate to the lockdown level over time. This is important as it will impact the final prediction.\n",
    "\n",
    "This graph should correlate to how much safer we are over time due to the lockdowns assuming that Lockdowns have a strong reduction in contact rate depending on lockdown level."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "{0: 0, 50: 0.5, 141: 0, 263: 1, 303: 0.6}\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(coefficients)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# The SIR model differential equations.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    #starting date is 3rd February 2020\n",
    "    #49 days\n",
    "    #1st lockdown is 23rd March - 23rd June taking 92 days\n",
    "    #122 days\n",
    "    #2nd Lockdown is 23rd October - 2nd December taking 40 days\n",
    "    \n",
    "def adjust_rate(contact_rate, day):\n",
    "    if day > 50:\n",
    "        contact_rate = GlobalContactRate - coefficients[50]\n",
    "        return contact_rate\n",
    "    if day < 150:\n",
    "        contact_rate = GlobalContactRate - coefficients[141]\n",
    "        return contact_rate\n",
    "    if day < 277:\n",
    "        contact_rate = GlobalContactRate - coefficients[263]\n",
    "        return contact_rate\n",
    "    if day < 317:\n",
    "        contact_rate = GlobalContactRate - coefficients[303]\n",
    "        return contact_rate\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        contact_rate = 0.6\n",
    "        return contact_rate\n",
    "\n",
    "# The SIR model differential equations.\n",
    "def deriv(state, t, N, beta, gamma):\n",
    "    S, I, R = state\n",
    "    \n",
    "    beta = adjust_rate(beta, t)\n",
    "    # Change in S population over time\n",
    "    dSdt = -beta * S * I / N\n",
    "    # Change in I population over time\n",
    "    dIdt = beta * S * I / N - gamma * I\n",
    "    # Change in R population over time\n",
    "    dRdt = gamma * I\n",
    "    return dSdt, dIdt, dRdt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This aspect of my work has two functions; Adjust Rate and deriv.\n",
    "\n",
    "adjust Rate: This allows me to change the global contact rate variable over time based on the coefficients that we defined at specific dates, this can be furthered by also reducing the infectivity of the virus based on when the Vaccinations came out, however it was here that the limitations of this method became clear.\n",
    "\n",
    "The limitation is that we are appying a reduction in contact rate over the entire population but a large part of the population doesn't neccesarrily apply lockdown rules to there daily lives or get the required vaccinations. this data also doesn't distinguish between age groups that change the recovery rate.\n",
    "\n",
    "My other function is deriv: This is a basic function applying the mathematic calculus in order to find the changes of cases over time. I found this calculation at: https://www.maa.org/press/periodicals/loci/joma/the-sir-model-for-spread-of-disease-the-differential-equation-model, this calculation can not be changed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "R0 is 1.8\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<AxesSubplot:xlabel='day'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 19,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Global Variables\n",
    "effective_contact_rate = 0.6\n",
    "GlobalContactRate = 0.6\n",
    "recovery_rate = 1/3\n",
    "R0 =  effective_contact_rate / recovery_rate\n",
    "#Computation of R value. isn't particullarly applied in the program but is useful to know what the program thinks our R value is\n",
    "print(\"R0 is\", R0)\n",
    "\n",
    "# start population of England look like?\n",
    "total_pop = 55980000\n",
    "recovered = 0\n",
    "infected = 1\n",
    "# Everyone not infected or recovered is susceptible\n",
    "susceptible = total_pop - infected - recovered\n",
    "\n",
    "# A list of days from our dataset.\n",
    "days = range(0, data[\"length\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "# differential equation to find the changes in susceptible, infected and recovered over time.\n",
    "ret = odeint(deriv,\n",
    "             [susceptible, infected, recovered],\n",
    "             days,\n",
    "             args=(total_pop, effective_contact_rate, recovery_rate))\n",
    "S, I, R = ret.T\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# putting information in a dataframe\n",
    "df = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    'suseptible': S,\n",
    "    'infected': I,\n",
    "    'recovered': R,\n",
    "    'day': days\n",
    "})\n",
    "#plots\n",
    "plt.style.use('ggplot')\n",
    "df.plot(x='day',\n",
    "        y=['infected', 'suseptible', 'recovered'],\n",
    "        color=['#bb6424', '#aac6ca', '#cc8ac0'],\n",
    "        kind='area',\n",
    "        stacked=False)\n",
    "df.plot(x='day',\n",
    "        y=['infected', 'recovered'],\n",
    "        color=['#bb6424', '#aac6ca', '#cc8ac0'],\n",
    "        kind='area',\n",
    "        stacked=False)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Global Variables:\n",
    "My Global Variables tells the programme the important factors about the disease such as the population, recovery rate, and contact rate.\n",
    "\n",
    "My programme then computes the changes of Susceptable, Infected and Recovered"
   ]

    "# What this graph shows us:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This result is an ideal progression of the pandemic, however in comparison to the real results the progression isn't realistic. in this model the infections peaked at 16 million very quickly however quickly died out, and before day 100 the infection is gone. Whereas in the real world the infection is still around 700 days later and even recently peaked in cases with the new omnicron variant."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Pros of this Model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Number of cases was actually very close to accurate. it predicted there would be 16 million cases however according to the bbc https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51768274, we are currently at  18.6 million cases in total. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can tell it more detail of decisions made by the government and it will have a real effect on the graph. An example of why this is useful is because if the training data on a time series analysis were to end just before a large peak of cases, such as a new variant of COVID, the prediction would be very inaccurate, however by adding this as a variable the prediction of a SIR model would very quickly adapt."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Cons of this Model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "According to an artical on the inefficiency of SIR models, https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-021-84055-6, \"Due to the lack of access to adequate information about this newly emerged pandemic, simple strategies such as SIR-based models have been implemented by several investigators. However, their accuracy and suitability for prediction of the COVID-19 disease course is a matter of debate\" This lack of accuracy is clearly seen in our implementation of a SIR model.\n",
    "\n",
    "This simple simulation can not completely take into account the factors that have a great impact in how a pandemic can spread which means no simulation from this model will be completely accurate."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Solution 2: AutoRegression for Time Series Forcasting"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Introduction to Autoregression"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "According to https://www.statisticshowto.com/autoregressive-model/: a Autoregressive model is a time series analysis tool that looks for correlation in data and uses that to forcast data in the future.\n",
    "\n",
    "For this it is finding a pattern in cases and will use that pattern to find cases in the future."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   ]

    "# Solution 3: Gaucien Processor Regressor for Time Series Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Introduction to Gaucien Processor Regressor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Gaucien Processor Regressor is a strong machine learning algorithm that uses a bayesian approach to regression. By looking at the trends of the data it is able to make minute changes to the prediction to maintain maximum accuracy while forcasting data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Application of Gaucien Processor Regression"
   ]
  },
  {

   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},

    "plt.plot(range(data_df_rev.shape[0]),(data_df_rev['newCases']))\n",

    "          fontsize=15,)\n",

   "source": [
    "data_df_rev['SMA_30(Cases)'] = data_df_rev.newCases.rolling(30, min_periods=14).mean()  #simple moving average of window of 30 days\n",
    "data_df_rev['SMA_14(Cases)'] = data_df_rev.newCases.rolling(14, min_periods=7).mean() #SMA of window of 14 days\n",
    "data_df_rev['CMA(Cases)'] = data_df_rev.newCases.expanding().mean() #cumulative moving average ... it does not perform well for this data as no historical data\n",
    "data_df_rev['EMA_0.3 (Cases)'] = data_df_rev.newCases.ewm(alpha=0.3, adjust=False).mean() #exponetial moving average might do well we may have to find right alpha\n",
    "\n",
    "data_df_rev['SMA_30(Deaths)'] = data_df_rev.newDeaths.rolling(30, min_periods=14).mean()  #simple moving average of window of 30 days\n",
    "data_df_rev['SMA_14(Deaths)'] = data_df_rev.newDeaths.rolling(14, min_periods=7).mean() #SMA of window of 14 days\n",
    "data_df_rev['CMA(Deaths)'] = data_df_rev.newDeaths.expanding().mean() #cumulative moving average ... it does not perform well for this data as no historical data\n",
    "data_df_rev['EMA_0.3 (Deaths)'] = data_df_rev.newDeaths.ewm(alpha=0.3, adjust=False).mean() #exponetial moving average might do well we may have to find right alpha\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here I am looking at simple moving averages over 30 or 14 days as to show data changes over periods of time. I'm also making a exponential moving average because it places a greater weight and significance on the most recent data points.\n",
    "\n",
    "Cumulative moving Average is less useful in this scenario, this is because it is better over years of time to analyse the effect of trends on the total average. In this model everything has a strong weight over cumulative average due to the low time the pandemics been around for."
   ]
  },

    "days = input('how many days ago would you like to predict from')\n",
    "days = int(days)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "train_data_Cases = newCases[30:(len(newCases)- days)].reshape(-1,1)         #split and reshape the array into 2 dim. Ignore first 30 data as it is 0 \n",
    "test_data_Cases = newCases[(len(newCases)- days):].reshape(-1,1)\n",
    "\n",
    "train_data_Deaths = newDeaths[30:(len(newDeaths)- days)].reshape(-1,1)         #split and reshape the array into 2 dim. Ignore first 30 data as it is 0 \n",
    "test_data_Deaths = newDeaths[(len(newDeaths)- days):].reshape(-1,1)            #This is for test"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This allows me to change the date of my train data, essentially telling my information at what point I would like to stop looking at data and start forcasting the future cases.\n",
    "\n",
    "I've allowed the user to change this variable as if there are a peak of cases or deaths just after the train data ends it will cause my forcasting program to be less accurate."
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.gaussian_process import GaussianProcessRegressor                             #import gaussian process regressor\n",
    "from sklearn.gaussian_process.kernels import Matern, WhiteKernel, ConstantKernel, RBF        \n",
    "kernel = ConstantKernel() + Matern(length_scale=3, nu=3/2) + WhiteKernel(noise_level=20)   #create a kernel by combining different standard functions\n",
    "gp1 = GaussianProcessRegressor(\n",
    "    kernel=kernel, \n",
    "    n_restarts_optimizer=10, \n",
    "    normalize_y=True,\n",
    "    alpha=0.5\n",
    ")                                                                                      "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here I am creating a kernal; This is a technique to find the relationship between my 2 variables 'time and cases/deaths'\n",
    "\n",
    "then I'm allowing my gaussian process regressor model to evaluate the kernal and make machine learning algorithms that will fit my forcasted data. "
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Pros of this model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This process is even good on smaller datasets"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Very Accurate analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Very Visual and easy to understand"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Cons of this model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Can not predict sudden large increases or decreases in trends."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Conclusions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Innefficiency of each model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There will never be a model that is perfect, and each will have cons that make them better or worst. Of the three models the most efficient was the Gaucien Processor Regression. It was able to make use of a regression kernal that found patterns in my data set and then created train data that perfectly forcasted my data. whereas the other models were widely innacurate."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Aspects that make for a good performing model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Accuracy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The most accurate model was Undeniably the Gaucien Processor Regression."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Readability"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Arima model is unreadable and impossable to get any valuable data from, this is because it is simply better fit for other purposes.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Gaucien Processor Regression model is very readable, and easy to analyse data from.\n",
    "\n",
    "The SIR Model is very readable but is not very useful, it tells the reader what the ideal scenario was and when it could of been over by but in this case the disease is too complex for this model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Fit for purpose"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The ARIMA Model is better at predicting/forcasting the change of prices, however it requires many years of data to be useful and isn't usefull for smaller datesets which makes it not fit for this purpose like I originally thought.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Gaucien Processor Regression is usefull at finding correlations of nearly random data sets and due to the unpredictability of a pandemic it is very fit for this purpose.\n",
    "\n",
    "The SIR Model is better at simulating data of a pandemic over time then predicting data, but due to it's simple execution is seemingly unfit for purpose"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Overall"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Overall, I found that the Gaucien Processor Regression is the best time series analysis out of my solutions."
